    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Medicaid in New York</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Greater New York Hospital Association president Kenneth E Raske letter on Sept 11 editorial that urged closing of loophole in Medicaid law that is being used by 17 states, including New York, to inflate their costs and extract more federal money than they are entitled to; says if Health Care Financing Administration decides to implement regulations changing Medicaid reimbursement rules, vital health insurance programs for low-income New Yorkers will be jeopardized</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Siphoning Money From Medicaid'' (editorial, Sept. 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Siphoning Money From Medicaid'' (editorial, Sept. 11):</p>
        <p>If the Health Care Financing Administration decides to carry out regulations changing Medicaid reimbursement rules, vital health insurance programs for low-income New Yorkers will be jeopardized.</p>
        <p>As you point out, if states are abusing the current Medicaid reimbursement system by using federal health care dollars for unauthorized non-health care purposes, then the government is right to stop the practice. But New York devotes its own funds, as well as 100 percent of the federal health care funds that would be lost under the changes being proposed, to innovative health insurance programs and health care to low-income residents.</p>
        <p>The proposed regulations would derail one of the country's most promising programs for the uninsured before it has even started.</p>
        <p>KENNETH E. RASKE  President, Greater New York  Hospital Association  New York, Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
